      • Introduction¶

      PISA is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. This survey examines;

      • how well students have learned the school curriculum,
      • how well prepared they are for life beyond school.

      Around 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the PISA 2012 assessment of reading, mathematics and science. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.

      To start us off, we need to upload these Libraries;

      • Numpy
      • Pandas
      • Matplotlib
      • Seaborn
      • Zipfile
      • Patches

# Read the pisa2012.csv file which is large with over 485492 rows and 636 columns 
pisa2012='pisa2012.csv'
import subprocess

def file_len(pisa2012):
    p = subprocess.Popen(['wc', '-l', pisa2012], stdout=subprocess.PIPE, 
                                              stderr=subprocess.PIPE)
    result, err = p.communicate()
    if p.returncode != 0:
        raise IOError(err)
    return int(result.strip().split()[0])+1

n_rows = file_len(pisa2012)
print (f'Exact number of rows: {n_rows}')

Structure of the Pisa dataset¶

The Pisa Dataset has 485490 students and 636 features that describes each of them.

Main features of interest¶

My main features of interest are as follows;

  1. The National study programme they are on
  2. Student's Family structure - both parents or single parenthood
  3. Availability of resources - internet and ICT resources.
  4. Family Wealth
  5. Immigration Status
  6. Family Possessions
  7. Teacher's Support
  8. The Student's performance under this conditions

Features in the dataset that support my investigation.¶

This PISA2012 dataset has 636 columns, but we will only look at a few varibles that will help us answer our questions;

  1. SchoolID
  2. Gender
  3. Age
  4. Country
  5. Family structure - both parents or single parenthood
  6. Availability of resources - internet and ICT resources.
  7. Wealth
  8. Immigration Status
  9. Teacher's Support
  10. Plausible Value in Mathematics, Reading and Science

This are the only columns we will retain in the dataset
